# Two rendering pipelines, one source format

Authors write fenced code blocks tagged with language `mermaid`. Two
pipelines consume them; never introduce a third without updating this rule:

- **Chat view** — `prepareMarkdownHtml` produces a pre-rendered HTML string
  (unchanged). `MessageMarkdown` uses `html-react-parser` to walk that
  string and replace every `<pre><code class="language-mermaid">` subtree
  with a `<MermaidBlock>` React component. The async
  `mermaid.parse` + `mermaid.render` sequence (see "Parse before render"
  below) lives in the `useMermaidRender` hook
  (`frontend/src/hooks/useMermaidRender.js`), which `MermaidBlock`
  consumes; the component itself owns only the diagram/source toggle,
  the lightbox modal state, and the error fallback wiring.
  `useMermaid` (called once in `MessageMarkdown`) bootstraps the mermaid
  singleton with `startOnLoad: false` and keeps the theme in sync with
  `ThemeModeContext`.

  The chat view has two **presentation surfaces** fed by a single
  `mermaid.render` per block: the inline `<MermaidBlock>` and an
  optional `<MermaidLightboxModal>` opened on click of the diagram body
  or the expand icon. The modal consumes the SVG already in
  `MermaidBlock`'s state via props and **never** calls `mermaid.render`,
  `mermaid.parse`, or `mermaid.initialize` itself. Theme flips
  propagate to the modal automatically: `useMermaidRender`'s
  `useEffect([source, darkMode])` regenerates the SVG, the new value
  flows to the modal as a prop, and React reconciles
  `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`. Adding a second `mermaid.render` call for
  the modal would be a third pipeline (forbidden) and would re-open the
  bomb-graphic risk that "Parse before render" closes.

  `mermaidRenderCache` and `mermaidRenderQueue` (both under
  `frontend/src/utils/`) wrap the chat-view pipeline with memoization
  and scheduling, **not** a third pipeline. Neither helper calls
  `mermaid.parse`, `mermaid.render`, or `mermaid.initialize` itself;
  the chat-view pipeline's owners (`useMermaidRender` and
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams`) remain the only sites that do. See
  "Render cache and queue" below for both contracts and the wire-up
  invariants the consuming render hook must preserve.

- **HTML export** — `cursor_view/export/mermaid.py::transform_mermaid_fences_to_html`
  rewrites mermaid fences to `<div class="mermaid">` blocks before
  Python-Markdown sees them. `load_vendored_mermaid_js` + `build_mermaid_init_script`
  inject the vendored bundle and an initializer tag before `</body>` so
  every exported file is self-contained (no network at view time).

# Modal pan/zoom/reset is presentation-only

`MermaidLightboxModal` adds interaction behavior over the SVG it
receives from `MermaidBlock` (drag pan, wheel zoom, toolbar zoom
in/out, and reset-to-fit), but that behavior is strictly DOM-transform
based:

- Pan/zoom state and math live in `frontend/src/hooks/useSvgPanZoom.js`
  (effects, refs, pointer/wheel handlers, identity-reset action) on
  top of pure helpers in `frontend/src/utils/svgPanZoomModel.js`
  (anchor-preserving zoom helper `zoomAtAnchor` plus its internal
  scale clamp; both shared so wheel zoom and button zoom round-trip
  through the same formula). The modal itself stays focused on
  layout: it reads the hook's outputs, applies them as a
  `translate(...) scale(...)` transform to a child layer wrapped
  inside an `overflow: hidden` viewport, and renders the toolbar.
- The modal, the hook, and the model must not call
  `mermaid.initialize`, `mermaid.parse`, or `mermaid.render` for
  pan/zoom/reset; those APIs remain owned by `useMermaidRender`
  (consumed by `MermaidBlock`) and the one-time singleton config
  in `useMermaid`. Re-rendering the SVG to zoom would re-open the
  bomb-graphic risk closed by "Parse before render" and would
  constitute a third pipeline (forbidden).
- Wheel zoom and button zoom share one canonical anchor-preserving
  zoom helper in `svgPanZoomModel`; the math assumes
  `transformOrigin: '0 0'` on the transform layer, so do not change
  that origin without re-deriving the helper. Wheel zoom anchors
  around the cursor, button zoom anchors around the viewport center.
- The wheel handler must call `event.preventDefault()` so the gesture
  does not chain into the surrounding `Dialog`/page scroll. Combined
  with `touchAction: 'none'` on the viewport, this also opts the
  surface out of native pinch-zoom and two-finger scroll on touch
  devices, which would otherwise fight the JS transform.
- Drag pan uses pointer events with `setPointerCapture` so a
  pointer-up outside the viewport still ends the drag. The viewport
  also sets `userSelect: 'none'` (and the `-webkit-` companion) to
  suppress the native text-selection flicker that would otherwise
  fire while dragging across SVG text labels.
- "Reset view" restores the identity transform
  (`scale: 1, translateX: 0, translateY: 0`). The modal's CSS already
  centers the SVG inside the transform layer (`display: flex` plus
  `& svg { maxWidth: 100%; maxHeight: 100% }`), so the identity
  transform *is* the fit-and-center baseline by construction; the
  hook does not measure the SVG to derive a per-diagram baseline.
  The hook re-applies identity on modal open and whenever the `svg`
  prop changes, so reopening the modal and theme-flip-driven SVG
  regenerations both start from the same predictable centered fit
  rather than inheriting a stale zoomed/panned state.
- Toolbar controls live in `MermaidZoomControls`
  (`frontend/src/components/MermaidZoomControls.js`) and render in
  the modal's toolbar row alongside `Close` rather than overlaid on
  diagram content. Disable zoom-out at `minScale` and zoom-in at
  `maxScale`; the hook exposes those booleans as `controls.canZoomOut`
  / `controls.canZoomIn` so the disabled state and the clamp logic
  cannot drift apart.
- The toolbar row is rendered only when `hasDiagram` is true; the
  defensive parse-error fallback branch (see "Graceful source
  fallback on parse error") never gets pan/zoom controls because
  there is no SVG to transform.

# BLOBs stay out of the cache

Rendered mermaid SVGs are **not** image attachments and must not land in
`chat_image`, `chat_message`, `chat_search_text`, `chat_search_fts`, or
any source-row hash input. See [`image-attachments.mdc`](image-attachments.mdc)
and [`sqlite-cursor-db.mdc`](sqlite-cursor-db.mdc).

# Theme sync

- `MermaidBlock` reads `darkMode` from `ThemeModeContext` and forwards
  it to `useMermaidRender`, whose effect re-runs when `darkMode`
  flips. The hook calls `mermaid.initialize` with
  `theme: darkMode ? 'dark' : 'default'` immediately before each
  `mermaid.render` call.
- `build_mermaid_init_script(theme_mode)` maps `"dark"` → `"dark"`,
  everything else → `"default"`, matching the `EXPORT_HTML_THEMES` palette
  logic in `cursor_view/export/themes.py`.
- The mermaid theme must never be hard-coded; it must always be derived from
  the same `theme_mode` / `darkMode` source that drives the surrounding UI.

# Parse before render

Both rendering pipelines that call `mermaid.render` must call
`mermaid.parse` on the same source first and skip `mermaid.render`
entirely when parse rejects. `mermaid.render` injects a "bomb" SVG
element directly into `document.body` as a side effect when its internal
parse fails, and that DOM mutation cannot be undone from the `.catch`
handler. Without the guard, every dark/light toggle on a chat that
contains an invalid diagram re-runs the failing render and leaves one
more orphaned bomb at the end of the page (the original symptom that
motivated the invariant — see the entry in
[`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc)). `mermaid.parse` is DOM-free; it
throws on invalid syntax without touching `document.body`, which is what
makes parse-first safe to run on every theme flip.

The two parse-first sites:

- `frontend/src/hooks/useMermaidRender.js` — the per-block render
  effect (consumed by `MermaidBlock`) awaits `mermaid.parse(source)`
  first, surfaces the parse error through the same source-fallback UI
  as a render-time error, and only allocates a render id and calls
  `mermaid.render` when parse succeeded. Theme flips re-run the
  effect, so the guard fires on every toggle, not just first mount.
- `frontend/src/utils/prerenderMermaidDiagrams.js` — the pre-paint pass
  awaits `mermaid.parse(source)` before `mermaid.render` for the same
  reason; this keeps the bomb out of `document.body` while the chat is
  still loading, before any `MermaidBlock` mounts.

A future third pipeline (per "Two rendering pipelines, one source
format") must adopt the same parse-first sequence.

# Theme-tagged prerender entries

`prerenderMermaidDiagrams` returns a Map whose values have the shape
`{ svg, error, darkMode }`. The third field carries the `darkMode`
value the entry was rendered against and exists so `MermaidBlock` can
detect a theme shift between prerender and mount. `MessageMarkdown`'s
`replaceNode` interceptor forwards each entry's `darkMode` to its
matching `MermaidBlock` as the `initialDarkMode` prop alongside
`initialSvg` and `initialError`; do not strip this field, and do not
introduce a third Map shape.

`useMermaidRender`'s `skipFirstRenderRef` (`MermaidBlock` forwards
the `initialSvg` / `initialError` / `initialDarkMode` props through
to the hook) may suppress the first-mount render only when the
prerender result is still authoritative for the current theme:

- An `initialError` entry qualifies unconditionally: the parse error
  message is theme-independent and the source-fallback UI is the same
  in both themes.
- An `initialSvg` entry qualifies only when `initialDarkMode === darkMode`
  in the hook's render context. A mismatch means the user toggled
  theme during `ChatDetail`'s loading window, the cached SVG was themed
  against the prior value, and the per-block effect must run on first
  mount so the diagram is re-themed.
- The no-prerender-data case (`initialSvg`, `initialError`, and
  `initialDarkMode` all `undefined`) cleanly degrades to "do not skip"
  because the boolean expression `Boolean(initialError) ||
  (Boolean(initialSvg) && initialDarkMode === darkMode)` is `false`.

This rule exists to close the chat-detail prerender-vs-toggle race
documented in [`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc): without the theme
match check, `skipFirstRenderRef` would suppress the very render that
would correct a theme-mismatched cached SVG, leaving valid diagrams
stuck in the prerender's theme until something else re-triggered the
per-block effect. The fix lives in the consumer (`useMermaidRender`)
rather than in the producer (`ChatDetail`'s fetch effect) because
adding `darkMode` to the fetch effect deps would refetch the chat over
the network on every theme toggle, which is a worse UX trade than the
sub-frame async-render window the consumer-side fix produces.

# Render cache and queue

`useMermaidRender`'s render effect (consumed by `MermaidBlock`)
routes its `mermaid.parse + mermaid.render` work through two
module-scope helpers in `frontend/src/utils/`. Both are pure
memoization / scheduling around the existing chat-view pipeline
(per "Two rendering pipelines, one source format" above): neither
helper calls `mermaid.parse`, `mermaid.render`, or
`mermaid.initialize` itself. Those APIs remain owned by
`useMermaidRender` and `prerenderMermaidDiagrams`.

## `mermaidRenderCache`

A module-scope `Map<key, svg>` keyed by
`${darkMode ? 'd' : 'l'}\0${source}`, session-lifetime, no
eviction. Two writers exist:

- `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` writes after every successful
  `mermaid.render` call — the cold-page prerender doubles as the
  cache-warmer. `ChatDetail`'s fetch effect drives it through
  three sequential outer phases so both themes' SVGs are in the
  session cache by the time the loading spinner clears, and the
  user's first toggle on the chat is a cache hit for every
  diagram regardless of toggle direction:

  1. **Phase A — markdown prep.** `Promise.all` over messages
     calling `prepareMarkdownHtml(message.content)` only. No
     mermaid state at all; this phase fans out independently of
     the singleton.
  2. **Phase B — active-theme prerender.** `Promise.all` over
     the Phase A output calling `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(
     m.renderedContent, darkMode)`. The return value populates
     each message's `mermaidSvgs` field.
  3. **Phase C — opposite-theme cache-warm.** `Promise.all` over
     the Phase A output calling `prerenderMermaidDiagrams(
     m.renderedContent, !darkMode)`. The return value is unused
     intentionally; the side effect we want is the
     `mermaidRenderCache` fill for `(source, !darkMode)`.

  The dual-theme prerender pair MUST NOT be nested inside a
  `Promise.all` over messages -- that was the
  cross-message-singleton-race shape now retired in
  [`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc). Each
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` call flips
  `mermaid.initialize({ theme: ... })` on the global mermaid
  singleton and then runs its own internal `Promise.all` over
  the diagrams in one message; if two interleaved per-message
  pairs ran concurrently, a B-pass call from one message would
  overwrite the singleton baseline mid-flight, and any other
  message's A-pass render that had not yet captured its config
  would pick up the flipped theme via mermaid's
  `processAndSetConfigs` `reset()`-to-baseline at the start of
  every `mermaid.render`, producing a wrong-themed SVG cached
  under `(source, darkMode)`. The three-phase shape gives each
  `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` call uncontested ownership of the
  singleton for its full lifetime by running all messages'
  active-theme prerenders together and awaiting completion
  before starting the opposite-theme pass; every concurrent
  render within a phase shares the same theme by construction.

  The trade-off versus a single-theme prerender is doubled
  prerender wall-time on diagram-heavy chats; the count
  threshold escape hatch (only warm both themes when `< N`
  diagrams) is flagged inline at the call site for if it ever
  becomes a noticeable load delay.
- `useMermaidRender`'s effect (consumed by `MermaidBlock`) writes
  after every successful `mermaid.render` call inside its queued
  task body. With the dual-theme prerender above, this writer
  fires only on cache misses introduced after chat load (e.g. a
  future "load more messages" path that streams in new diagrams
  not seen by the initial prerender).

Errors deliberately stay out of the cache. Parser messages can
evolve across mermaid versions, and a transient render failure
should be re-evaluated on the next attempt rather than poisoning
the cache permanently. The cache hit branch in `useMermaidRender`
calls `setSvg(cachedSvg); setRenderError(null);` and returns; it
does not call `mermaid.parse` or `mermaid.render` itself.

The cache is safe with respect to "Parse before render"
**by construction**: cache writes only happen on the success path of
`mermaid.render`, which itself only runs after a successful
`mermaid.parse`. Therefore: cache hit ⇒ source previously parsed
cleanly ⇒ safe to reuse the SVG without re-running either
`mermaid.parse` or `mermaid.render`. The bomb-graphic risk only
fires when invalid syntax reaches `mermaid.render`; cached entries
were produced from valid syntax. A consumer that reads the cache and
calls `setSvg(cachedSvg)` is **not** required to call
`mermaid.parse` first — the cache contract makes that redundant.

## `mermaidRenderQueue`

A module-scope FIFO queue with concurrency 1, implemented as a
promise chain. Each enqueued task awaits the previous chain tail
before running, and the chain advances by appending a
`.catch(() => {})` fork so a thrown task does not poison subsequent
tasks. The caller's own promise still rejects on task error.

Without the queue, a theme toggle on a chat with N visible uncached
diagrams fires N concurrent `mermaid.render` calls all racing the
JS thread, freezing the page for the union of their durations. The
queue serializes them so the JS thread stays interactive between
tasks.

The queue runs **after** the cache check: a cache hit returns its
SVG immediately and never enters the queue. With the dual-theme
prerender at chat load (see the `prerenderMermaidDiagrams` writer
above), the cache is fully warm for both `(source, true)` and
`(source, false)` keys before the user can interact, so the queue
is empty for the first theme toggle and every toggle after.
Diagrams introduced after the initial prerender (e.g. a future
streaming-messages path) are the only sites that re-introduce
queue traffic, and only on their first toggle in each theme.

## Wire-up invariants

`useMermaidRender`'s effect (consumed by `MermaidBlock`) must:

1. Run the cache check before queuing. A cache hit writes
   `setSvg(cachedSvg); setRenderError(null);` and returns — no
   queue, no `mermaid.parse`, no `mermaid.render`.
2. Increment `latestRef` on every effect run, including cache-hit
   runs, so any in-flight queued task from a prior run sees its
   captured `id` go stale and bails its post-await state writes.
   Without this, a queued task for an old `(source, darkMode)`
   could overwrite a newer cache-hit's correct `setSvg` with a
   stale render.
3. Keep `mermaid.initialize` inside the queued task body, not at
   effect time. The task may run with arbitrary delay after the
   effect (other queued renders ahead of it); a later effect's
   `mermaid.initialize` would otherwise overwrite the singleton
   between this task's queue position and its `mermaid.render`
   call, producing an SVG themed against the wrong palette.
4. Write to the cache only on the success path of `mermaid.render`.
   Errors stay out. `prerenderMermaidDiagrams`'s writer respects
   the same constraint.
5. Keep the existing post-await `latestRef` stale checks at every
   `await` boundary inside the queued task body (after
   `mermaid.parse`, after `mermaid.render`, in the render-catch).
   The pre-await stale check at the top of the queued task is a
   perf optimization (skip wasted work for superseded tasks); the
   post-await checks are correctness (do not write stale results
   into React state).

# Graceful source fallback on parse error

When `mermaid.parse` rejects (the dominant case, gated by the
parse-before-render section above) or `mermaid.render` rejects (the
post-parse backstop), `MermaidBlock` surfaces the error message via a
`<Typography color="error">` caption and forces `mode = 'source'` so the
raw fence text is always visible. This is deliberate graceful
degradation — not a [`known-bugs.mdc`](known-bugs.mdc) `TODO(bug):`.
Do not silently swallow parse errors or render a blank box.

`MermaidLightboxModal` mirrors the same fallback shape (Typography
error caption above a `<pre><code>` of the raw source) so the invariant
holds across both chat-view presentation surfaces. The fallback panel
itself lives in
`frontend/src/components/MermaidLightboxFallback.js`; the modal renders
it in the non-`hasDiagram` branch and owns no theming for it directly,
which is what keeps the modal under the `react-components.mdc` size
limit and isolates "diagram surface" from "source fallback". In normal
use `MermaidBlock` hides the expand affordance whenever `renderError`
is set, so the modal's fallback branch is defensive — it covers a
future caller that opens the modal without first checking the
success-only gate, and prevents the modal from ever painting a blank
Paper.

`MermaidBlock` additionally runs an auto-close-on-error effect keyed
on the `isErrored` boolean (not the `renderError` message string) so
that a late-detected parse failure during a theme flip while the
modal is open closes the modal cleanly instead of surfacing the
defensive fallback. The boolean dep keeps re-firing limited to
state-of-error transitions, not message-text changes of an
already-failed parse.

# Escape before inlining (HTML export)

`transform_mermaid_fences_to_html` runs `html.escape` on the mermaid body
before wrapping it in `<div class="mermaid">`. This is the actual XSS
boundary for authored content. Mermaid's `securityLevel: "strict"` is
belt-and-braces on top; removing the `html.escape` call is not safe even
if `securityLevel` is set.

# Markdown and JSON exports leave fences verbatim

`cursor_view/export/markdown.py` emits message content unchanged.
`mermaid`-tagged fences render on any GitHub-flavored markdown viewer
without any transformation from us. Do not add diagram rendering to the
Markdown or JSON export paths.

# Vendored mermaid.min.js

The UMD browser build lives at `cursor_view/export/vendor/mermaid.min.js`
and is committed to the repo. It is **not** a generated build artifact of
this project; it is a vendored third-party asset, analogous to a
`third_party/` or `vendor/` directory in other projects.

`cursor_view/export/vendor/` is the **only** place vendored third-party
JS/CSS assets may live. Do not add a second `vendor/` dir elsewhere.

## Update procedure

When bumping the mermaid version:

1. Update `"mermaid"` in `frontend/package.json` and run `npm install`
   inside `frontend/`.
2. Copy `frontend/node_modules/mermaid/dist/mermaid.min.js` to
   `cursor_view/export/vendor/mermaid.min.js`.
3. Overwrite `cursor_view/export/vendor/VERSION.txt` with the new version
   string (no trailing newline).
4. Commit all three files together.

The frontend (`mermaid` npm package) and the export (`mermaid.min.js`) must
track the **same major version** to avoid diagram-syntax drift between the
chat view and HTML exports.

# Prose references to mermaid fence syntax

When writing plan files, rules, or other documentation that needs to mention
the literal text of a mermaid opening fence, do **not** use a 4-backtick
inline-code span to wrap it. Cursor's chat renderer treats the inner triple
backticks as an opening fence and produces a parse error. Use phrasing such
as "a fenced code block tagged with language `mermaid`" instead.
